When comparing floating-point numbers in test cases, it's common to encounter small differences due to the way floating-point numbers are represented in computers. To handle this issue and make the comparison more tolerant of slight variations, you can use a comparison with a tolerance value instead of exact equality.

In Google Test, you can use the `ASSERT_NEAR` macro to compare floating-point numbers with a specified tolerance. This allows for a comparison that considers floating-point imprecision within a certain range.

Here's how you can modify the test case to use `ASSERT_NEAR` with a tolerance value:

```cpp
TEST(GcSetForegroundTest, TestFunctionality) {
    struct graphics_gc_priv gc;
    struct color test_color = {32768, 49152, 65535, 8192}; // Test color values

    gc_set_foreground(&gc, &test_color); // Call the function with test data

    // Verify that the fr, fg, fb, and fa values are approximately equal within a tolerance
    ASSERT_NEAR(gc.fr, test_color.r / 65535.0, 1e-10); // Tolerance of 1e-10 for example
    ASSERT_NEAR(gc.fg, test_color.g / 65535.0, 1e-10);
    ASSERT_NEAR(gc.fb, test_color.b / 65535.0, 1e-10);
    ASSERT_NEAR(gc.fa, test_color.a / 65535.0, 1e-10);
}
```

In this modified test case, the `ASSERT_NEAR` macro is used to compare the values within a tolerance range (in this case, `1e-10`). You can adjust the tolerance value based on the precision required for your specific scenario.

By using `ASSERT_NEAR` with a suitable tolerance value, you can make the test case more flexible and robust when comparing floating-point numbers, allowing for small variations while still ensuring the correctness of the results.
